<TextWithNodes><Node id="0" />The jewellery group <Node id="20" />Signet<Node id="26" /> <Node id="27" />yesterday<Node id="36" /> illustrated the transatlantic consumer confidence divide with figures showing British sales roaring ahead, while its <Node id="154" />US<Node id="156" /> arm suffered a downturn.
<Node id="182" />Signet<Node id="188" />'s American business, which includes the huge <Node id="234" />Kay<Node id="237" /> chain and accounts for <Node id="261" />73%<Node id="264" /> of group sales, recorded a <Node id="292" />3.4%<Node id="296" /> fall in like-for-like sales in the <Node id="332" />three months to the end of July<Node id="363" />.<Node id="364" />

<Node id="366" />Most analysts had expected worse, following disappointing results from <Node id="437" />Signet<Node id="443" />'s main <Node id="451" />US<Node id="453" /> rivals.<Node id="461" />

<Node id="463" />This week<Node id="472" /> <Node id="473" />Zales<Node id="478" />, the biggest jewellery chain in the <Node id="515" />US<Node id="517" />, was forced to issue a profits alert after a <Node id="563" />9.7%<Node id="567" /> dip in like-for-like sales, while smaller <Node id="610" />US<Node id="612" /> operator <Node id="622" />Reeds<Node id="627" /> announced a <Node id="640" />13.7%<Node id="645" /> sales decline.<Node id="660" />

<Node id="662" />British sales have lost none of their sparkle as consumers, buoyed by lower interest rates, ignore signs of global recession. Same-store sales from <Node id="810" />Signet<Node id="816" />'s <Node id="819" />H Samuel<Node id="827" /> and <Node id="832" />Ernest Jones<Node id="844" /> shops were up <Node id="859" />9.3%<Node id="863" />, with the best gains - <Node id="887" />16.9%<Node id="892" /> - coming from the <Node id="911" />Ernest Jones<Node id="923" /> outlets, which sell bigger ticket baubles.<Node id="966" />

<Node id="968" />That was down on the <Node id="989" />10.9%<Node id="994" /> improvement recorded in the <Node id="1023" />first quarter of the year<Node id="1048" />, but better than analysts expected.<Node id="1084" />

<Node id="1086" />Terry Burman<Node id="1098" />, <Node id="1100" />Signet<Node id="1106" />'s chief executive, insisted that <Node id="1140" />Kay<Node id="1143" /> and the group's other <Node id="1166" />US<Node id="1168" /> brand, <Node id="1176" />Jared<Node id="1181" />, were more than holding their own in a difficult trading environment. "While a decline in like-for-like sales always disappoints, we take some satisfaction from a further gain in market share and the continued resilience of our business compared to the competition."<Node id="1448" />

<Node id="1450" />Total group sales for the half-year were ahead <Node id="1497" />19.8%<Node id="1502" /> at <Node id="1506" />629.7m pounds<Node id="1519" />, or <Node id="1524" />1.7%<Node id="1528" /> on a like-for-like-basis.<Node id="1554" />

<Node id="1556" />Mr Burman<Node id="1565" /> said the group's transatlantic reach, with 1,007 stores in the <Node id="1629" />US<Node id="1631" /> and 599 in <Node id="1643" />Britain<Node id="1650" />, was a big advantage in the present situation of diverging economic fortunes.<Node id="1728" /></TextWithNodes>
